Git Commands Guide for Project Team (Frontend,
Backend, Data Engineer, ML Engineer)
This document lists the common Git commands each team member should use while working on
the shared GitHub repository for the project. The workflow is the same for all roles but organized
here separately for clarity.

Frontend Developer Workflow
• Clone the repository: git clone
• Enter the project folder: cd influencer-platform
• Always pull the latest code before starting work: git pull
• Create a branch for frontend work: git checkout -b frontend-feature
• Work inside the frontend/ folder
• Stage changes: git add .
• Commit changes: git commit -m 'Added frontend UI page'
• Push branch to GitHub: git push origin frontend-feature

Backend Developer Workflow
• Clone the repository: git clone
• Enter the project folder: cd influencer-platform
• Pull latest changes: git pull
• Create backend branch: git checkout -b backend-api
• Work inside backend/ folder
• Add changes: git add .
• Commit code: git commit -m 'Added backend API endpoints'
• Push code: git push origin backend-api

Data Engineer Workflow
• Clone the repository: git clone
• Enter project directory: cd influencer-platform
• Pull latest project updates: git pull
• Create branch for data work: git checkout -b data-pipeline
• Work inside data_engineering/ folder
• Add dataset or scripts: git add .
• Commit work: git commit -m 'Added dataset and preprocessing scripts'
• Push branch: git push origin data-pipeline

Machine Learning Engineer Workflow
• Clone the repository: git clone
• Navigate to project: cd influencer-platform
• Pull latest updates: git pull
• Create ML branch: git checkout -b ml-model
• Work inside ml_model/ folder
• Add model files: git add .
• Commit model: git commit -m 'Added creator recommendation model'
• Push branch: git push origin ml-model

Basic Git Commands Summary (Used by Everyone)
• git clone → download project from GitHub
• git pull → get latest updates from teammates
• git checkout -b → create a new branch
• git add . → stage all changes
• git commit -m 'message' → save changes locally
• git push origin → upload changes to GitHub
